<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08160e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08160e">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08160e"> 160(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> grass of 3 cows / nonage / share &amp; share alike / legit &amp; illegit</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> &ldquo;The childe being oftentimes left in nonage,&rdquo; says Campion, &ldquo;could never defend his patrimony, but by the time he grow to a competent age &hellip; he also taketh his turn,&rdquo; &hellip; The entire land belonged to the clan, and was held theoretically in common, and a redistribution made on the death of each owner &hellip; All sons, illegitimate as well as legitimate, shared and shared alike, holding the property between them in undivided ownership. It was less the actual land than the amount of grazing it afforded which constituted its value. Even to this day a man, especially in the West of Ireland, will tell you that he has &ldquo;the grass of three cows,&rdquo; or &ldquo;the grass of six cows,&rdquo; as the case may be. <small> Emily Lawless, <a name="ELIS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ELIS"><cite title="source">Ireland (Story of Nations series</cite></a> (192?) 27-8</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
